[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] In philosophy, a fundamental distinction exists between **abstract** and **concrete** entities.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] While there is no universally accepted definition, common examples illustrate the difference: numbers, sets, and ideas are typically classified as abstract objects, whereas plants, dogs, and planets are considered concrete objects.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] *Causal influence* – Concrete objects can cause and be affected by other entities (e.g., a rock breaking a window), whereas abstract objects (e.g., the number 2) lack causal powers and do not cause anything to happen in the physical world.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] *Metaphysical relation* – In metaphysics, concrete objects are specific, individual things (particulars), while abstract objects represent general concepts or categories (universals).
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] *Ontological domain* – Concrete objects belong to the physical realm (or both the physical and mental realms), whereas abstract objects belong to neither.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Another view is that it is the distinction between contingent existence versus necessary existence; however, philosophers differ on which type of existence here defines abstractness, as opposed to concreteness.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Despite this diversity of views, there is broad agreement concerning most objects as to whether they are abstract or concrete, such that most interpretations agree, for example, that rocks are concrete objects while numbers are abstract objects.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract objects are most commonly used in philosophy, particularly metaphysics, and semantics.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] They are sometimes called ***abstracta*** in contrast to ***concreta***.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] The term *abstract object* is said to have been coined by Willard Van Orman Quine.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract object theory is a discipline that studies the nature and role of abstract objects.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] It holds that properties can be related to objects in two ways: through exemplification and through encoding.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Concrete objects exemplify their properties while abstract objects merely encode them.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] This approach is also known as the dual copula strategy.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] The type–token distinction identifies physical objects that are tokens of a particular type of thing.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] The "type" of which it is a part is in itself an abstract object.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Abstract objects have often garnered the interest of philosophers because they raise problems for popular theories.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] In ontology, abstract objects are considered problematic for physicalism and some forms of naturalism.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Historically, the most important ontological dispute about abstract objects has been the problem of universals.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] In epistemology, abstract objects are considered problematic for empiricism.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] If abstracta lack causal powers and spatial location, how do we know about them?
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] It is hard to say how they can affect our sensory experiences, and yet we seem to agree on a wide range of claims about them.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] In philosophy of religion, the existence of abstract objects is sometimes considered a problem for divine aseity, which, for example, prompted the Christian philosopher William Lane Craig to argue against uncreated abstract objects.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Other Christian philosophers, such as Peter van Inwagen, have conversely argued *for* their existence, seeing no conflict between them and theism.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Some, such as Ernst Mally, Edward Zalta and arguably, Plato in his Theory of Forms, have held that abstract objects constitute the defining subject matter of metaphysics or philosophical inquiry more broadly.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] To the extent that philosophy is independent of empirical research, and to the extent that empirical questions do not inform questions about abstracta, philosophy would seem especially suited to answering these latter questions.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] In modern philosophy, the distinction between abstract and concrete was explored by Immanuel Kant and G.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Gottlob Frege said that abstract objects, such as propositions, were members of a third realm, different from the external world or from internal consciousness.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Another popular proposal for drawing the abstract–concrete distinction contends that an object is abstract if it lacks causal power.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] A causal power has the ability to affect something causally.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Thus, the empty set is abstract because it cannot act on other objects.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] One problem with this view is that it is not clear exactly what it is to have causal power.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] For a more detailed exploration of the abstract–concrete distinction, see the relevant *Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy* article.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] In the 2010s, there was some philosophical interest in the development of a third category of objects known as the **quasi-abstract**.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Quasi-abstract objects have drawn particular attention in the area of social ontology and documentality.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Specifically, the ability to have temporal location, but not spatial location, and have causal agency (if only by acting through representatives).
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] These characteristics are exhibited by a number of social objects, including states of the international legal system.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Jean Piaget uses the terms "concrete" and "formal" to describe two different types of learning.
[src:adverb/abstract-and-concrete] Concrete thinking involves facts and descriptions about everyday, tangible objects, while abstract (formal operational) thinking involves a mental process.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In descriptions of the Japanese language, an **adjectival noun**, **nominal adjective**, **copular noun**, **adjectival verb** (形容動詞, *keiyō dōshi*), **quasi-adjective**, **pseudo-adjective**, or ***na*-adjective**, is a noun that can function as an adjective by taking the particle 〜な *-na*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] (In comparison, regular nouns can function adjectivally by taking the particle 〜の *-no*, which is analyzed as the genitive case.) Adjectival nouns constitute one of several Japanese word classes that can be considered equivalent to adjectives.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In their attributive function, Japanese adjectival nouns function similarly to English noun adjuncts, as in "*chicken* soup" or "*winter* coat" – in these cases, the nouns "chicken" and "winter" modify the nouns "soup" and "coat", respectively.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Japanese adjectival nouns can also be used predicatively – in that use, they do not take the *-na* suffix, but normally combine with forms of the copular verb.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The current term for the so-called "adjectival nouns" is *keiyō dōshi* (形容動詞).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] 'form' or 'figure' or 'appearance' or 'description') refers to the semantic aspect of these words as qualifying the state or condition of a noun (名詞, *meishi*); and *dōshi* (動詞; lit.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Historically, this term was used tentatively by some grammarians, such as Matsushita Daizaburō, for words that are now called *keiyōshi* (形容詞; lit.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The "attributive adjective" sense was applied in a different way by yet other grammarians, such as Hamada Kenjirō and Ōwada Takeki, who used *keiyō dōshi* for "verb" forms that occur attributively, such as *hashiru* (走る; lit.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The first use of *keiyō dōshi* for so-called "*na*-adjectives" is attributed to Haga Yaichi.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The Japanese term is not necessarily at odds with the English term *adjectival noun*, since in traditional Japanese grammar, *keiyō dōshi* includes the copula, while the adjectival noun in the analysis described here does not include the copula.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] For example, in the traditional grammar, *kirei da* is a keiyō dōshi and *kirei* is its stem; in the analysis here, *kirei* is an adjectival noun and *kirei da* is its combination with the copula.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Considering the copula is a kind of verb and *kirei* is a kind of noun syntactically, both terminologies make sense.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Grammatically, these words are similar to nouns, or more technically, nominals, which function attributively (like adjectives).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Aside from these differences, Japanese adjectival nouns and regular nouns behave the same way in terms of grammar.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] They are variously referred to as "adjectival verbs" (literal translation), "adjectival nouns" (nouns that function adjectivally), "*na* adjectives" (function as adjectives, take *na*), and "*na* nominals" (nominals that take *na*).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] For example, Eleanor Harz Jorden refers to them as "*na*-nominals" in her textbook *Japanese: The Spoken Language*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In fact, by some analyses, nouns and *na*-nominals are fundamentally grammatically the same, where 〜の vs. 〜な when used attributively is simply a conventional stylistic complementary distribution, with 〜の／〜な being allomorphs.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] This view is reinforced by the fact that some words, such as 特別 *tokubetsu* "special", can take either a 〜の or a 〜な, depending on the phrase.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Ultimately, 〜な is an abbreviation of 〜にある, used to use a noun attributively (compare modern 〜である, which is a more recent form), while 〜の is the genitive case; see etymology, below.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In traditional Japanese grammar, adjectival nouns are considered "inflectional", *katsuyō*, like verbs and *i*-adjectives, rather than non-inflectional *hikatsuyōgo* (非活用語) or *mukatsuyōgo* (無活用語), like nouns.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] This is a point of disagreement in current Japanese grammar, and authors such as Uehara (1998) argue that instead, adjectival nouns should be classed with nouns as non-inflectional.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The claim that *na*-adjectives are inflectional rests on the claim that the syllable *da* 'is', usually regarded as a "copula verb", is really a suffix – an inflection.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Thus, *hon* 'book', generates a one-word sentence, *honda* 'it is a book', not a two-word sentence, *hon da*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] However, numerous constructions seem to be incompatible with the suffixal copula claim.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In Japanese, questions are formed by adding the particle *ka* (or in colloquial speech, just by changing the intonation of the sentence).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] On the basis of such constructions, Uehara (1998) finds that the copula is indeed an independent word, and that regarding the parameters on which *i*-adjectives share the syntactic pattern of verbs, the nominal adjectives pattern with pure nouns instead.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In Late Old Japanese (below), a separate kind of *tari* adjectival nouns developed alongside the existing *nari* ones (*nari, tari* were the conclusive forms, while *naru, taru* were the attributive forms).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] These are generally referred to as ト・タル形容動詞 (*to, taru keiyōdōshi*) or タルト型活用 (*taruto-kata katsuyō* – “taru, to form conjugation”), and can also function adverbially with 〜と *-to,* instead of the 〜に *-ni* which is mostly used with な nominals.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] See *taru* adjectives for further discussion in English, and 形容動詞#タルト型活用 for Japanese.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] A few *nari* adjectival nouns followed a similar path to *tari* adjectival nouns, becoming *naru* adjectives in Modern Japanese (analogous to *taru* adjectives), rather than *na* adjectives as most *nari* adjectival nouns did.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Old Japanese has one type of adjectival noun with the following inflections.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Late Old Japanese has two types of adjectival nouns: *nar-* and *tar-*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The newly developed *tar-* inflections are used in kanbun kundoku (reading a Chinese text in Japanese).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Early Middle Japanese has two types of adjectival nouns: *na-* and *tar-*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Late Middle Japanese has two types of adjectival nouns: *na* and *t-*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The early half of Early Modern Japanese as exhibited in the Kamigata region has a single type of adjectival noun with the following inflections.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The later half of Early Modern Japanese as found in Edo has a single type of adjectival noun with the following inflections.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] These forms are identical to the modern forms.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] There is one type of adjectival noun in modern usage, with inflections as follows.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Japanese adjectival nouns differ in etymological origin from adjectival verbs.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Whereas adjectival verbs are almost entirely native in origin, the class of adjectival nouns comprises mostly foreign loanwords and a small subset of polymorphemic native words.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] All words listed in this section take the attributive *-na* and predicative *-da* copula.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] In addition to loanwords, within the class of adjectival nouns also exists a small subset of native Japanese words (wago).
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] These words are argued to be polymorphemic in nature, with the latter *-ka*, *-raka*, *-yaka* being a suffix that creates an adjectival noun.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Nishiyama (1999) asserts that this helps to distinguish native adjectival nouns from native adjectival verbs.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] All forms of the copula (the vehicle for the inflection of adjectival nouns) can be considered to derive from two infinitive forms, *ni* and *to*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Because the copula lacked any other forms, secondary conjugations with the verb *ari* were used.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The original *ni ari* and *to ari* contracted to form *nari* and *tari*.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] To derive the modern forms *na* and *da*, changes such as the following have been proposed.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The infinitive form *ni* is still in widespread use (e.g.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] *hen ni naru*, "become strange"), but the form *to* has become a much rarer alternative for use with adjectives.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] The internal properties of Japanese adjectival nouns can be analysed either through a lexical features approach or through a Distributed Morphology approach.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Miyagawa argues that Japanese adjectival nouns can be classified using Noam Chomsky's lexical feature system.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Under this system, Japanese adjectival nouns are classed similarly to English pure adjectives [+V, +N].
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] However, because Japanese also has adjectival verbs with the lexical property [+V], it is observed that Japanese adjectival nouns and English pure adjectives are distinct.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Within the tree structures, the word root combines with the functional category n0 to become a noun, then combine with the functional head a0 to form an adjective.
[src:adverb/adjectival-noun-japanese] Both nouns and adjectives contain the root-n0 combination, and it is the presence of a0 that results in the appearance of the attributive copula *-na*.
[src:adverb/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:adverb/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:adverb/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:adverb/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:adverb/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:adverb/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:adverb/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:adverb/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:adverb/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:adverb/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:adverb/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:adverb/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:adverb/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:adverb/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:adverb/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:adverb/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:adverb/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:adverb/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:adverb/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:adverb/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:adverb/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:adverb/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:adverb/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:adverb/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:adverb/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:adverb/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:adverb/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:adverb/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:adverb/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:adverb/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:adverb/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:adverb/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:adverb/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:adverb/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:adverb/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:adverb/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:adverb/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:adverb/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:adverb/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:adverb/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:adverb/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:adverb/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:adverb/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:adverb/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:adverb/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:adverb/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:adverb/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:adverb/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:adverb/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:adverb/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:adverb/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:adverb/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:adverb/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:adverb/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:adverb/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:adverb/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:adverb/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:adverb/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:adverb/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:adverb/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:adverb/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:adverb/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:adverb/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:adverb/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:adverb/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:adverb/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:adverb/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:adverb/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:adverb/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:adverb/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:adverb/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:adverb/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:adverb/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:adverb/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:adverb/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:adverb/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:adverb/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:adverb/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:adverb/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:adverb/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:adverb/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:adverb/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:adverb/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:adverb/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:adverb/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:adverb/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:adverb/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:adverb/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:adverb/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:adverb/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:adverb/adverb] An **adverb** is a word or an expression that generally modifies a verb, an adjective, another adverb, a determiner, a clause, a preposition, or a sentence.
[src:adverb/adverb] Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, or level of certainty by answering questions such as *how*, *in what way*, *when*, *where*, *to what extent*.
[src:adverb/adverb] This is called the adverbial function and may be performed by an individual adverb, by an adverbial phrase, or by an adverbial clause.
[src:adverb/adverb] Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.
[src:adverb/adverb] The English word *adverb* derives (through French) from Latin *adverbium*, from *ad-* ('to'), *verbum* ('word', 'verb'), and the nominal suffix *- ium*.
[src:adverb/adverb] The term implies that the principal function of adverbs is to act as modifiers of verbs or verb phrases.
[src:adverb/adverb] An adverb used in this way may provide information about the manner, place, time, frequency, certainty, or other circumstances of the activity denoted by the verb or verb phrase.
[src:adverb/adverb] Adverbs can also be used as modifiers of adjectives, and of other adverbs, often to indicate degree.
[src:adverb/adverb] Adverbs thus perform a wide range of modifying functions.
[src:adverb/adverb] The major exception is the function of modifier of nouns, which is performed instead by adjectives (compare *she sang loudly* with *her loud singing disturbed me*; here the verb *sang* is modified by the adverb *loudly*, whereas the noun *singing* is modified by the adjective *loud*).
[src:adverb/adverb] The word *even* in the first sentence is an adjective, since it is a prepositive modifier that modifies the noun *numbers*.
[src:adverb/adverb] When the function of an adverb is performed by an expression consisting of more than one word, it is called an adverbial phrase or adverbial clause, or simply an adverbial.
[src:adverb/adverb] In English, adverbs of manner (answering the question *how?*) are often formed by adding *-ly* to adjectives, but flat adverbs (such as in *drive fast*, *drive slow*, and *drive friendly*) have the same form as the corresponding adjective.
[src:adverb/adverb] Many other adverbs, however, are not related to adjectives in this way; they may be derived from other words or phrases, or may be single morphemes.
[src:adverb/adverb] Examples of such adverbs in English include *here, there, together, yesterday, aboard, very, almost*, etc.
[src:adverb/adverb] Where the meaning permits, adverbs may undergo comparison, taking comparative and superlative forms.
[src:adverb/adverb] In English this is usually done by adding *more* and *most* before the adverb (*more slowly, most slowly*), although there are a few adverbs that take inflected forms, such as *well*, for which *better* and *best* are used.
[src:adverb/adverb] For more information about the formation and use of adverbs in English, see English adverbs.
[src:adverb/adverb] For other languages, see § In other languages below, and the articles on individual languages and their grammars.
[src:adverb/adverb] Adverbs are considered a part of speech in traditional English grammar, and are still included as a part of speech in grammar taught in schools and used in dictionaries.
[src:adverb/adverb] However, modern grammarians recognize that words traditionally grouped together as adverbs serve a number of different functions.
[src:adverb/adverb] Some describe adverbs as a "catch-all" category that includes all words that do not belong to one of the other parts of speech.
[src:adverb/adverb] A logical approach to dividing words into classes relies on recognizing which words can be used in a certain context.
[src:adverb/adverb] When this approach is taken, it is seen that adverbs fall into a number of different categories.
[src:adverb/adverb] For example, some adverbs can be used to modify an entire sentence, whereas others cannot.
[src:adverb/adverb] Even when a sentential adverb has other functions, the meaning is often not the same.
[src:adverb/adverb] Words like *very* afford another example.
[src:adverb/adverb] *Perry is very fast* is grammatical, but not *Perry very won the race*.
[src:adverb/adverb] These words can modify adjectives but not verbs.
[src:adverb/adverb] On the other hand, there are words like *here* and *there* that cannot modify adjectives.
[src:adverb/adverb] *The sock looks good there* is grammatical, but not *It is a there beautiful sock*.
[src:adverb/adverb] The fact that many adverbs can be used in more than one of these functions can confuse the issue, and it may seem like splitting hairs to say that a single adverb is really two or more words that serve different functions.
[src:adverb/adverb] However, this distinction can be useful, especially when considering adverbs like *naturally* that have different meanings in their different functions.
[src:adverb/adverb] Rodney Huddleston distinguishes between a *word* and a *lexicogrammatical-word*.
[src:adverb/adverb] Grammarians find difficulty categorizing negating words, such as the English *not*.
[src:adverb/adverb] Although traditionally listed as an adverb, this word does not behave grammatically like any other, and it probably should be placed in a class of its own.
[src:adverb/adverbial-clause] An **adverbial clause** is a dependent clause that functions as an adverb.
[src:adverb/adverbial-clause] That is, the entire clause modifies a separate element within a sentence or the sentence itself.
[src:adverb/adverbial-clause] As with all clauses, it contains a subject and predicate, though the subject as well as the (predicate) verb are omitted and implied if the clause is reduced to an **adverbial phrase** as discussed below.
[src:adverb/adverbial-clause] An adverbial clause begins with a subordinating conjunction—sometimes called a trigger word.
[src:adverb/adverbial-clause] According to Sidney Greenbaum and Randolph Quirk (*Greenbaum* and *Quirk*, 1990), adverbial clauses function mainly as adverbial adjuncts or disjuncts but differ in syntax from adverbial phrases and adverbial prepositional phrases, as indicated below.
[src:adverb/adverbial-clause] Unlike adverbial clauses, adverbial phrases contain neither an explicit subject nor a predicate.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] In grammar, an **adverbial genitive** is a noun declined in the genitive case that functions as an adverb.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] In Old and Middle English, the genitive case was productive, and adverbial genitives were commonplace.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] While Modern English does not fully retain the genitive case, it has left various relics, including a number of adverbial genitives.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] The adverbial genitive also survives in a number of stock phrases; for example, in "I work days and sleep nights", the words *days* and *nights* are analyzed as plural nouns but are in fact derived historically from the genitive or instrumental cases of *day* and *night*.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] (That they function as adverbs rather than as direct objects is clear from the rephrasing "I work during the day and sleep at night.") The modern British expression "Of an afternoon I go for a walk" has a similar origin, but uses the periphrasis "of + *noun*" to replace the original genitive.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] This periphrastic form has variously been marked as used "particularly in isolated and mountainous regions of the southern United States" and as having "a distinctly literary feel".
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] German uses the genitive as a productive case, in addition to adverbial genitive expressions.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] The adverbial suffix *-erweise* added to adjectives is derived from the feminine singular genitive adjective ending *-er* agreeing with the noun *Weise* 'manner'.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] For example, the adverb *glücklicherweise* 'fortunately' can be analyzed as *glücklicher Weise* 'fortunate way [genitive]', i.e.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] 'in a fortunate way' or more explicitly ‘in a manner of good fortune’ (which also hints at the possessive role of the case).
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] The conjunction *falls* ('if') is the genitive of *Fall* 'case'.
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] Likewise for *keinesfalls*/*keineswegs* ('by no means of'), *andernfalls* ('otherwise' i.e. ‘another way of’).
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] The preposition *angesichts* ('in view of') is the genitive of *Angesicht* ('face').
[src:adverb/adverbial-genitive] The time expressions *morgens*, *mittags*, *abends*, *nachts*, *eines Tages* (one day) and *eines Nachts* (one night; analogized with *eines Tages*, though *Nacht* is feminine) use the adverbial genitive.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] In linguistics, an ***adverbial phrase*** ("**AdvP**") is a multi-word expression operating adverbially: its syntactic function is to modify other expressions, including verbs, adjectives, adverbs, adverbials, and sentences.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Some grammars use the label **adverb phrase** to denote an adverbial phrase composed entirely of adverbs versus an *adverbial phrase*, which might not contain an adverb.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial phrases can be divided into two types: complementary phrases and modifying phrases.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] For example, *very well* is a complementary adverbial phrase that complements "sang" in the sentence "She sang *very well*".
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] More specifically, the adverbial phrase *very well* contains two adverbs, *very* and *well*: while *well* qualifies the verb to convey information about the manner of singing.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] The following examples illustrate some of the most common types of adverbial phrases.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] All adverbial phrases appear in bold; when relevant, the head of each adverbial phrase appears in square brackets.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] The heads of each of the following adverbial phrases are degree adverbials (written "Deg" in syntactic trees).
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Degree adverbials modify adjacent adverbs (that is, an adverb that is lower in the syntactic tree than the degree adverbial).
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Degree adverbials are commonly used in English to convey the intensity, degree, or focusing of an adjacent adverb.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Modifying adverbial phrases combine with a sentence, and the removal of the adverbial phrase yields a well-formed sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Just as adjective phrases function attributively to give additional information about an adjacent noun, the modifying adverbial phrases illustrated in (5) to (7) function as secondary predicates that give additional temporal information about the sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Complement adverbial phrases are much less common than their modifying counterparts.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial phrases functioning as complements usually arise when an adverb licenses a complement as a selectional requirement.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Nearly all of these complements license an adjoining prepositional phrase.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Below are a few examples of complement adverbial phrases.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] The following sentences illustrate the difference between adverbs, adverbial phrases, and adverbial clauses.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] In the first example, "soon" is an adverb (as distinct from a noun or a verb), which is a type of adverbial.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] In the second sentence, the modifying phrase "in an hour" has the same syntactic function (that is, to act adverbially and modify the base of the sentence "I'll go to bed"), though it does not contain an adverb.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] This modifying phrase includes a preposition and a determiner phrase, and functions as an adverbial, thus making it an adverbial phrase.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] In the third example, we see a whole clause functioning as an adverbial; it is termed an adverbial clause.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Functionally, the term adverbial refers to all structures that can take the position of an adverb on a phrase structure level.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbs modify the functional categories that occur in a sentence and may also be treated as predicates which are functionally open and require one or more arguments to be satisfied.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] It has been argued that the distribution of adverbs is largely conditioned by their lexical nature or thematic properties.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Main classes of adverbials are used to distinguish the functional properties of the adverbs within the phrase.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Each class has subcategories, that refer more specifically to the syntactic and semantic properties of the adverbial.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] There is no distinct terminology for these classes used universally in literature, though adverbials are often classified into their functional categories.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] The major classes of adverbials are adjunct, disjunct and conjunct.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Conjunct: contextualizes relationships between text.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] The class of subjunct is usually placed within adjunct class as it is difficult to distinguish between the two.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] The subcategories for adverbials have more universally used terminology and often refer to the nature of the adverb within each phrase.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Most literature focuses on the specific categories of adjunct adverbials.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adjunct adverbials are the most often discussed class of adverbials, when discussing distribution in English.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Complement adverbials are also seen to display similar attributes as adjuncts.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Distinguishing between these is a matter of the overt realization of the phrase and is discussed below.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] More possible subcategories of adjunct adverbials are: degree, speaker-oriented, duration, focusing, viewpoint, modality and frequency.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Conjunct adverbials, sometimes called linking adverbials, are used to connect clauses together and surface in a clause-initial position in English.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Disjunct adverbials, also referred to as modal adverbials, have subcategories which relay a speakers interpretation of what appears lower in the clause.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Subjunct adverbials are not often discussed as a class of its own in literature.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] As the distinction of these subcategories as subjunctive depend on the role the adverbial takes within the phrase, a subordinate role, and when not in this structure will be in the adjunct class.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbials can be adjuncts, complements, conjuncts, or disjuncts.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Most commonly, adverbial phrases are either complements or adjuncts.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adjunct adverbial phrases provide additional information and are part of the structure of the clause, but are optional.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Complements are elements of an utterance that complete the meaning of the noun or sentence in which it is being used.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Unlike adjuncts, they are necessary to complete the meaning of a given sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial complement is the term used to identify an adverbial phrase that is necessary to the meaning of the verb or utterance.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial complements always appear after the verb that they modify.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] If the verb is intransitive, the complement will appear directly after the verb; if the verb is transitive, the complement will appear after the verb's direct object.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] A test to identify whether or not an adverbial phrase is a complement or adjunct is to remove the phrase in question from the sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] If the sentence no longer makes sense or if its meaning is altered heavily, then the adverbial element is a complement.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] If the meaning is still intact, it is an adjunct.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] One phenomenon occurring frequently in sentences that involve adverbial phrases is adverbial fronting, where the adverbial phrase moves to the front of a sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Work on both this phenomenon, as well as comparing the movement of adverbial phrases to this syntactic position to typical movement and topicalization of arguments has been covered by Haegeman.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] There is a difference between fronted adjuncts (in this case, adverbial phrases) and topicalized arguments.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial phrases behave as adjuncts, and that serves as particularly useful in discussions regarding adverbial phrases and their movement, as well as their integration into syntactic structure.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial phrases are different across languages.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Like English, adverbial phrases are the parts of a sentence that add circumstantial information.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] French often requires using adverbial phrases where English is satisfied with a simple adverb.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Placements of adverbs in adverbial phrases is usually determined by the category of adverbs.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] In English, placement of adverbs can sometimes be arbitrary, where some adverbs may be found in front or after the verb or even at the beginning of the sentence, while French adverbs have much stricter rules and can be difficult.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] There is a contrast between verb–adverbial order in French and adverbial–verb order in English.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Adverbial expressions are formed in French, by combining prepositions with nouns (or noun phrases), adjectives (adjective + a noun), adverbs, or a series of words.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] While movement is slightly different from English, suffixation is similar.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Most French words that end in *-ment* are adverbs, and the majority of the time their English equivalents end in *-ly*: *généralement* – "generally".
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] In a brief overview on how adverbs are used in the overall phrase structure, in French there is an expansion in the word due to a derivation adjective adjective-to-adverb conversion process, namely, *-ment* suffixation.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] Similarly, in English, words have the *-ly* suffixation added at the end of adverbs in adverbial phrases.
[src:adverb/adverbial-phrase] However, this process of adding suffixation at the end of the adverbial word in French, is not as productive as *-ly* suffixation in English, and some adjectives are incompatible with it.
[src:adverb/adverbial] In English grammar, an **adverbial** (abbreviated **adv**) is a word (an adverb) or a group of words (an adverbial clause or adverbial phrase) that modifies or more closely defines the sentence or the verb.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Adverbials most commonly take the form of adverbs, adverb phrases, temporal noun phrases or prepositional phrases.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Many types of adverbials (for instance: reason and condition) are often expressed by clauses.
[src:adverb/adverbial] An adverbial is a construction which modifies or describes verbs.
[src:adverb/adverbial] When an adverbial modifies a verb, it changes the meaning of that verb.
[src:adverb/adverbial] This may be performed by an adverb or a word group, either considered an adverbial: for example, a prepositional phrase, a noun phrase, a finite clause or a non-finite clause.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Adverbial complements (i.e. obligatory adverbial) are adverbials that render a sentence ungrammatical and meaningless if removed.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Adjuncts: These are part of the core meaning of the sentence, but if omitted still leave a meaningful sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Conjuncts: These link two sentences together.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Disjuncts: These make comments on the meaning of the rest of the sentence.
[src:adverb/adverbial] All verb- or sentence-modifying adjuncts are adverbials, but some adverbials are not adjuncts.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Prepositions (*in*, *out*, etc.) may be used adverbially to indicate direction or location.
[src:adverb/adverbial] In some grammar models, negators such as "not" and "never" are considered adverbs with the function of negating adverbial clauses.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Often ignored, expletives may take up many adverbial syntactic functions.
[src:adverb/adverbial] Pragmatically and semantically, they often serve as intensifiers, boosting the content of the clause they appear in.
